Here's an example of Spark code in Scala that reads a CSV file and performs some basic data transformations:

```
import org.apache.spark.sql.SparkSession

object MySparkApp {
  def main(args: Array[String]) {
    // create a SparkSession instance
    val spark = SparkSession.builder()
      .appName("My Spark App")
      .master("local")
      .getOrCreate()

    // read a CSV file into a DataFrame
    val df = spark.read
      .format("csv")
      .option("header", "true")
      .option("inferSchema", "true")
      .load("file.csv")

    // show the first 5 rows of the DataFrame
    df.show(5)

    // select specific columns and rename them
    val selected = df.select(
      df("id").as("custom_id"),
      df("price").as("item_price")
    )

    // calculate the average price of items
    val avgPrice = df.agg(
      avg("price").as("avg_price")
    )

    // print the results
    selected.show(5)
    avgPrice.show()
  }
}
```

This code creates a SparkSession instance and uses it to read a CSV file into a DataFrame. It then performs some data transformations, such as selecting specific columns and calculating the average price of items. Finally, it shows the results of the transformations in the console.

Here is an example of Spark code in Scala that reads data from MongoDB, performs some transformations and computations, and writes the result back to MongoDB:

```scala
import org.apache.spark.sql.SparkSession
import com.mongodb.spark.MongoSpark
import com.mongodb.spark.config.{ReadConfig, WriteConfig}
import org.mongodb.scala.bson.collection.mutable.Document

object MongoDBProcessor {
  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
    // create a SparkSession
    val sparkSession = SparkSession.builder()
      .appName("MongoDB Processor")
      .master("local")
      .getOrCreate()

    val readConfig = ReadConfig(Map("uri" -> "mongodb://localhost:27017/myDB.myCollection"))
    val writeConfig = WriteConfig(Map("uri" -> "mongodb://localhost:27017/myDB.myOutputCollection"))

    // read data from MongoDB and create a DataFrame
    val df = MongoSpark.load(sparkSession, readConfig)

    // perform some transformations and computations on the DataFrame
    val resultDf = df.groupBy("category").sum("value").toDF("category", "total_value")

    // write the result back to MongoDB
    MongoSpark.save(resultDf.write.option("collection", "myOutputCollection"), writeConfig)
  }
}
```

This code creates a SparkSession and uses it to read data from MongoDB into a DataFrame. It then performs some transformations and computations on the DataFrame, such as grouping by category and summing the value column. Finally, it writes the result back to MongoDB in a collection named "myOutputCollection". The code uses the `MongoSpark` class and `ReadConfig` and `WriteConfig` objects to configure the read and write operations to MongoDB.

Here is an example of Spark code in Scala that reads data from a Cassandra database, performs some transformations and computations, and writes the result to a PostgreSQL database:

```scala
import org.apache.spark.sql.SparkSession
import org.apache.spark.sql.cassandra._
import org.apache.spark.sql.functions.avg
import org.postgresql.Driver

object CassandraToPostgres {
  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
    // create a SparkSession
    val spark = SparkSession.builder()
      .appName("Cassandra To Postgres")
      .master("local")
      .config("spark.sql.catalog.cassandracatalog", "com.datastax.spark.connector.datasource.CassandraCatalog")
      .getOrCreate()

    // configure Spark to access Cassandra
    val cassandraConfig = Map(
      "spark.cassandra.connection.host" -> "localhost",
      "spark.cassandra.auth.username" -> "cassandra",
      "spark.cassandra.auth.password" -> "cassandra",
      "spark.cassandra.output.consistency.level" -> "ANY"
    )

    // read data from Cassandra and create a DataFrame
    val df = spark.read.cassandraFormat("mytable", "mykeyspace", cassandraConfig).load()

    // perform some transformations and computations on the DataFrame
    val resultDf = df.groupBy("category").agg(avg("value").as("avg_value"))

    // configure Spark to access Postgres
    val postgresConfig = Map(
      "driver" -> "org.postgresql.Driver",
      "url" -> "jdbc:postgresql://localhost/mydatabase",
      "dbtable" -> "mytable",
      "user" -> "postgres",
      "password" -> "postgres"
    )

    // write the result to Postgres
    resultDf.write.mode("append").jdbc(postgresConfig("url"), postgresConfig("dbtable"), postgresConfig)
  }
}
```

This code creates a SparkSession and uses it to read data from a Cassandra database into a DataFrame. It then performs some transformations and computations on the DataFrame, such as grouping by category and calculating the average of the value column. Finally, it writes the result to a PostgreSQL database, using the `jdbc` method and specifying the driver, JDBC URL, table name, username, and password for the PostgreSQL database. The code uses the `cassandraFormat` method and `cassandraConfig` object to configure Spark to access the Cassandra database. The `outputMode` is set to "append" since we want to add the result to an existing table in the PostgreSQL database.

Here is an example of Spark code in Scala that reads data from a MySQL database, performs some transformations and computations, and writes the result to a CSV file:

```scala
import org.apache.spark.sql.{SaveMode, SparkSession}

object MySQLToCSV {
  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
    // create a SparkSession
    val spark = SparkSession.builder()
      .appName("MySQL To CSV")
      .master("local")
      .getOrCreate()

    // read data from MySQL and create a DataFrame
    val url = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydatabase"
    val table = "mytable"
    val props = new java.util.Properties()
    props.setProperty("user", "username")
    props.setProperty("password", "password")
    val df = spark.read.jdbc(url, table, props)

    // perform some transformations and computations on the DataFrame
    val resultDf = df.groupBy("category").count()

    // write the result to a CSV file
    resultDf.write.mode(SaveMode.Overwrite).option("header", "true").csv("output.csv")
  }
}
```

This code creates a SparkSession and uses it to read data from a MySQL database into a DataFrame. It then performs some transformations and computations on the DataFrame, such as grouping by category and counting the number of rows for each category. Finally, it writes the result to a CSV file, using the `write` method, specifying the output format, and setting the `option` for header to true. The `mode` is set to "Overwrite" since we want to replace any existing output file with the new result. The code uses the `jdbc` method to read data from MySQL and specifies the JDBC URL, table name, and properties for user and password.

Here's an example of Spark code in Scala that reads data from a Parquet file, transforms it, and stores the output as a compressed text file in Hadoop:

```scala
import org.apache.spark.sql.SparkSession

object ParquetToText {
  def main(args: Array[String]): Unit = {
    // create a SparkSession
    val spark = SparkSession.builder()
      .appName("Parquet To Text")
      .master("local")
      .getOrCreate()

    // read data from Parquet and create a DataFrame
    val df = spark.read.parquet("input.parquet")

    // perform some transformations on the DataFrame
    val resultDf = df.filter("age > 30")
      .select("name", "age", "salary")
      .orderBy("salary")

    // write the result to compressed text files in Hadoop
    resultDf.rdd.map(_.mkString("\t")).saveAsTextFile("hdfs://localhost:9000/output", classOf[org.apache.hadoop.io.compress.GzipCodec])
  }
}
```

This code creates a SparkSession and uses it to read data from a Parquet file into a DataFrame. It then performs some transformations on the DataFrame, such as filtering out rows with age less than or equal to 30 and selecting only the name, age, and salary columns. Finally, it writes the result to compressed text files in Hadoop using the `rdd` method to convert the DataFrame to an RDD, `mkString` method to format each record as a tab-separated line of text, and `saveAsTextFile` method to write the RDD as text files. The output files are compressed using the `GzipCodec` class, which is specified as a parameter to the `saveAsTextFile` method.

